<RP Category='HEAD_OF_STATE_TAG'><HR>President</HR> Bush</RP> used an attack on his honesty by Gov. Bill Clinton as an occasion to mount his sharpest assault yet on his rival's fitness for office. 

<RP Category='HEAD_OF_STATE_TAG'>The <HR>President</HR></RP> -- on the third stop of a train trip through Wisconsin intended to project an image of confidence and momentum -- then unleashed a scorching recital of what he called Mr. Clinton's deceptions and reversals on seven issues, including his draft history, his use of marijuana and his positions on free trade, right-to-work laws and the Persian Gulf war. BILL CLINTON

Gov. Bill Clinton returned to <RP Category='HEAD_OF_STATE_TAG'><HR>President</HR> Bush</RP>'s base in the South and accused him of appealing to regional prejudice with a message that changes as he moves around the country. 

"In one state he says I'm too liberal," <RP Category='HEAD_OF_STATE_TAG'><HR>Governor</HR> Clinton</RP> said in Georgia.

He ridiculed the notion that Gov. Bill Clinton's leadership in Arkansas had prepared him for the White House, but he made his most blistering attacks against <RP Category='HEAD_OF_STATE_TAG'><HR>President</HR> Bush</RP>. 

<RP Category='HEAD_OF_STATE_TAG'><HR>President</HR> Bush</RP>: 10:30 A.M., CNN Newsmaker Sunday, interview.
